        <td class="comment-text"><div><span class="comment-copy">Using the md5 algorithm, without any iteration count (adaptation for increases in hashing speed over time) is a recipe for disaster.  Instead, use &#39;bf&#39;:  gen_salt(&#39;bf&#39;).  See more, including how to do a custom crack with a few billion salted hashes a second at <a href="http://codahale.com/how-to-safely-store-a-password/" rel="nofollow">codahale.com/how-to-safely-store-a-password</a></span> &ndash;&nbsp;<a href="/users/507544/nealmcb" title="757 reputation" class="comment-user">nealmcb</a> <span class="comment-date" dir="ltr"><span title="2011-03-28 00:01:48Z" class="relativetime-clean">Mar 28 '11 at 0:01</span></span></div></td>
    </tr>
            
    <tr id="comment-6179431" class="comment">
        <td></td>
        <td class="comment-text"><div><span class="comment-copy">@Tchalvak correct - you no longer have to provide your own salt data.  In fact the gen_salt also encodes the algorithm, which should really be &#39;bf&#39; as I note above - see the reference for more.  Given the use of &#39;bf&#39;, this answer is far superior to the one by rook.</span> &ndash;&nbsp;<a href="/users/507544/nealmcb" title="757 reputation" class="comment-user">nealmcb</a> <span class="comment-date" dir="ltr"><span title="2011-03-28 00:07:51Z" class="relativetime-clean">Mar 28 '11 at 0:07</span></span><span class="edited-yes" title="this comment was edited"></span></div></td>
