        <td></td>
        <td class="comment-text"><div><span class="comment-copy">Err, could you clarify the statement &quot;The salt should be a large randomly generated value&quot;?  Would I add that random value salt via the traditional means of string concatenation?

Does: <code>update account set pswhash = crypt(&#39;global salt&#39; || &#39;new password&#39; || &#39;user created date&#39;, gen_salt(&#39;sha256&#39;)) where account_id = 5</code>
 or something like that actually make sense for creating the initial hash?

Or am I missing something about the crypt() function?</span> &ndash;&nbsp;<a href="/users/69993/kzqai" title="5630 reputation" class="comment-user owner">Kzqai</a> <span class="comment-date" dir="ltr"><span title="2010-04-15 18:27:04Z" class="relativetime-clean">Apr 15 '10 at 18:27</span></span><span class="edited-yes" title="this comment was edited"></span></div></td>
    </tr>
            
    <tr id="comment-2663855" class="comment">
        <td></td>
        <td class="comment-text"><div><span class="comment-copy">Yes,  use string concatenation of the random value, also use the digest function. 
<code>pswhash = digest(&#39;global salt&#39;||&quot;password&quot;||primary_key, &quot;sha256&quot;)</code>  Using the id makes sure the resulting hash is unqie even if 2 people both use the same password and create an account on the same day.  You could make some improvements to the salt generation,  but this is a lot better than most implementations i have seen.</span> &ndash;&nbsp;<a href="/users/183528/rook" title="30987 reputation" class="comment-user">Rook</a> <span class="comment-date" dir="ltr"><span title="2010-04-15 19:04:04Z" class="relativetime-clean">Apr 15 '10 at 19:04</span></span><span class="edited-yes" title="this comment was edited"></span></div></td>
    </tr>

        </tbody>
    
        </table>
    </div>
    <a id="comments-link-2647173" class="comments-link" data-comments-count="3" title="expand to show all comments on this post">show <b>3</b> more comments</a>
</td>
</tr>
   
    </table>
